+Review this implementation plan for a local R conjoint-analysis deliverable. The required script will load projoint/exampleData1, reshape exactly choice1:choice8 plus choice1_repeated_flipped, estimate profile-level analytical corrected marginal means for 24 levels, and use explicit set_qoi profile-level AMCE contrasts with default clustering/IRR. It will estimate crime level2 vs level1 and reverse, and Housing Cost (three levels) with every possible baseline, one contrast per fit. A generated table will report crime contrasts and MMs; a 340-470 word memo will say AMCEs are reference-dependent, binary crime reversal only flips sign, compare MMs, use housing examples, and avoid claiming unique dominance. It will generate one 300dpi horizontal MM-range PNG. Acceptance checks validate count/identities/output. Is there any substantive or implementation pitfall in this plan, especially around corrected estimates, contrast CIs, and the bounded claim?

